[2] UK (England, Bolton)
Date: Sat 8 Dec 2012
Source: The Bolton news [edited]
http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/districtnews/districtatog/10097189.School_and_nursery_hit_by_outbreak_of_measles/


A measles outbreak has hit a Bolton secondary school and a nursery, with 31 children coming down with the illness. The majority of the cases were in the last few days among pupils at Harper Green School, Farnworth and babies at a nursery in Bromley Cross.

Now, parents are being urged to get any children who have not had the MMR jab, or who have not had the 2nd booster injection, immunised to stop the spread of the disease. It is thought to have spread among the secondary school children who have not had their MMR jab, or who have not had their 2nd booster. Babies affected at the nursery are thought to be under 12.5 months old, the age when they are immunised.

In 2011 in Bolton, there was just one case of measles, but so far this year [2012], there have been 31 confirmed cases and 7 possible cases. Immunisation levels in Bolton are currently at 96.3 per cent, higher than the national threshold of 95 per cent [for elimination of measles virus infection]. But in 1998, immunisation levels of babies dropped after controversial research was published which claimed to link the MMR jab with autism. At its lowest point, the rate was just 84 per cent.

There has been a huge rise in measles cases across the UK this year [2012], and, in Greater Manchester, there have been 98 confirmed cases this year, compared to 21 in 2011. Of these, the majority are in Wigan and Bolton, with 15 cases part of a national outbreak amongst the traveller [Roma] community. In September 2012, 3 children living in the Hall Lane travellers' camp, Moses Gate, were diagnosed with measles. The current outbreak is not linked to those cases.

Of the children affected in the recent scare, 2 needed hospital treatment. Staff from the HPA have visited both the school and the nursery and immunised any children who have not had the MMR jab or the booster. A pregnant member of staff at the school and another staff member with health complications were sent home as a precaution.

Harper Green deputy head Sara Cain said the outbreak seemed to have been contained, and there had been no new cases this week. She added: "We had a few children who had contracted measles. Generally, these were children who did not have the MMR and were slightly more susceptible.

Health protection specialist Graham Munslow, from NHS Bolton, said it was the highest number of cases in Bolton in more than 12 years. "It is not like chicken pox; measles is much more damaging to children."

