[3] UK (Wales, Swansea Bay)
Date: Thu 6 Dec 2012
Source: South Wales Evening Post [edited]
http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/12-new-cases-measles-confirmed/story-17515806-detail/story.html


Twelve new cases of measles in children and young people have been diagnosed in the past week, public health officials have confirmed. Three patients have been treated in hospital but have all now been released. Six schools across the Swansea Bay area are said to have children with the highly infectious disease. Letters have now been sent to parents of children in all schools in Swansea and Neath Port Talbot warning of an epidemic. The letter sent by Dr Jorg Hoffmann, consultant in Communicable Disease Control Mid and West Wales Health Protection Team, urges parents to make sure their children are vaccinated.

Measles is highly contagious and is generally spread from person to person by respiratory droplets such as coughs and sneezes. Early symptoms include a high temperature, cough, painful red eyes, and sometimes small white spots inside the mouth. A red, blotchy rash appears around 3 days later, usually starting on the face and then spreading down the rest of the body. Any person with a rash should stay at home for 5 days after the start of the rash.

The best way to get protection from measles is by vaccination. In the UK, each child should have the 1st MMR vaccine just after their 1st birthday and the 2nd between the ages of 3 and 5 years. If your child is aged one or older and missed being vaccinated, or if you yourself have not been, you and your child can still be vaccinated.

[Byline Rebecca Davies]

