Asia
------
[5] China (Yunnan)
Date: Tue 24 Dec 2012
Source: Yunnan Daily [in Chinese, machine trans. edited]
http://www.kaixian.tv/roll/n2835352c8.shtml


Measles is a serious hazard to the health of children with acute respiratory diseases. Measles is highly contagious and prone to occur as epidemics. In 2012, cases of measles have been fewer than in 2011. But in some provinces such as Hubei, Xinjiang, Guangdong, Qinghai, and Sichuan, the number of cases recorded in 2012 has been higher than reported previously.

As of 22 Nov 2012, the situation in Yunnan province in particular has been grim, with 336 confirmed cases reported since the beginning of the year, an increase of 208.26 percent compared to the same period in 2011 (109 cases), which placed the province under great pressure to react to this situation. The Health Department of Yunnan Province, the province the CDC regards as the most important in the struggle to combat measles virus infection, instructed the province to initiate a comprehensive vaccination programme to raise population immunity, starting within 14 days from Wed 6 Dec 2012.

Measles vaccination is planned for children aged 8 months to 4 years old, born on or after 1 Jan 2008. Children with no history of measles vaccination should be vaccinated with 2 doses of measles vaccine.

Measles vaccine contraindications:
(1) Children suffering from serious diseases, acute or chronic infection, fever, and with immunodeficiency disease or long-term use of immunosuppressive agents.
(2) Children with a history of allergies (especially those allergic to egg protein, and with a neomycin allergy).

Notes on vaccination:
(1) Children fasting or fatigued should not be vaccinated to prevent fainting.
(2) After inoculation, children should rest, be allowed to drink plenty of water, and avoid becoming chilled.
(3) A minority of children may exhibit swelling at the site of inoculation, fever, or exhibit an allergic reaction. Therefore, vaccinees should be kept under observation for a period of 30 minutes following vaccination.
(4) Children should not be bathed on the day of vaccination.

