[6] Myanmar (Kachin)
Date: Thu 29 Nov 2012
Source: Mizzima News [in Burmese, trans. Mod.YMA, edited]
http://www.mizzimaburmese.com/news/inside-burma/10496-2012-11-29-12-00-29.html


A responsible person from the Kachin Independence Organisation (KIO) mentioned that measles infection is spreading among children under 12 years old in a Kachin refugee camp at area No. 6 on the Myanmar-China border, and they are providing vaccination to the children. A local authority, U Dwel Pe Sar, says that only one or 2 children had measles at the beginning of November 2012, but now more than 40 children have the infection. Thus, the health department from KIO provided vaccination for the children in the camp last week.

He says: "The infection is transmitted to many children, but with no fatalities yet. We have provided vaccination and medical staff. They think the children in the camp had not received vaccine prior to this outbreak."

Now, there are more than 800 people in this camp. The people ran away from their villages due to warfare and now stay in this camp. Since the children had not been vaccinated earlier, infection has spread in the camp. Measles infection can spread rapidly and can be fatal if severe. Thus, vaccination should be provided to the children in order to prevent the infection.

A 10-day measles vaccination campaign was funded by UNICEF and WHO and was carried out in all states and regions during March 2012.

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[The newswire reports a measles outbreak among unvaccinated children in a Kachin refugee camp in November 2012. Up to 5 Nov 2012, there have been 1973 confirmed measles cases in Myanmar reported to the World Health Organization (see more at: http://www.who.int/immunization_monitoring/diseases/measlesreportedcasesbycountry.pdf).

For a map of Myanmar with states, see http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/burma_pol_96.jpg.

